Moral Dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The government's takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac represents a massive bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses had continued to grow in the face of falling home prices.
Now that the government is fully backing Fannies and Freddies' debts, American taxpayers will have to bear all the costs that are not covered by the insufficient financial resources of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in the most openly capitalist country in the world?
Do the venerable principles of capitalism not include the idea that those who believed in the real estate bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers have to suffer for their mistakes now?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral issues of the current financial crisis were clearly outlined.
But they are not.
Above all, it is unclear whether the bailout will actually cost U.S. taxpayers in the end. It may prevent further systemic effects that would otherwise force the financial sector and thus the global economy to its knees.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify does not mean they do not exist.
In addition, the bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as being backed by an implicit guarantee from the US government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a rescue action by the U.S. government could undermine confidence in government securities and, because they are associated with them, also in other financial instruments.
The problems extend far beyond the US economy.
The world economy has been driven in recent years by remarkable speculative booms and crashes in asset values, raising questions of trust as well as fairness.
Similarly, in many other countries, the real estate sector is currently experiencing similar peaks, and they may be facing the same struggles – and the same moral dilemmas – that the US economy is currently undergoing.
And the problem is not only the housing markets.
The stock markets are also like that.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose by a factor of 5 between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The S&P 500 in India rose by a factor of 5 in real terms between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost a third of its value.
Similar ups and downs in stock markets have occurred in many other countries.
As long as they continued, the boom phases preceding these crashes led to overheating in these economies.
Now, since they have reversed their positions, a loss of confidence could seize the world economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts may be necessary—not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people will react when, in the face of collapsing markets, help fails to arrive.
People's reactions to these events depend on their emotions and their sense of justice.
The described ups and downs have caused a significant redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested in the stock market or the real estate market did well or poorly depending on the timing.
People will judge the fairness of these results based on what they were told and the unspoken promises they inferred from it.
What were the people in all these countries told about the markets into which they invested their money?
Did everything really match the truth?
Unfortunately, there's no way to find out.
Politics can only react generally and cannot handle each case individually.
We know that the economic growth of recent times has been spectacular in many countries.
But were the capital investments sold at too high a price in their respective markets?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere lured people into the belief that boom times would bring prosperity for all?
It is certain that, although there may have been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations – the majority of the losers in this game are not starving.
But we cannot carelessly conclude from this that all her losses should be left untouched.
The nagging problem is one of "Faith and Trust."
National economies flourish only when "faith and trust" prevail.
The current situation, in which speculative booms have driven the world economy – and now, after their collapse, are driving it into recession – suggests that people who have praised certain capital investments have done so in bad faith.
Take the investors who held Fannie and Freddie bonds.
Although the U.S. government never officially promised to come to their aid in times of crisis, it established a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to assess their strength in an annual report.
But this agency has never even admitted that there was a housing bubble.
The top leaders of the government never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is in the process of transforming and discovering capitalism and its power over national economies.
Yet capitalism relies on trust and faith.
A perceived unfair treatment can be deadly for economic growth, because it means that people lose trust in companies and therefore are less willing to make their valuable capital and labor available to them.
Is such a result morally preferable to a bailout?
